4. Measurement of ffs(M 2Z )

Distributions of these 15 event shape observables were measured [12] using a sample of approximately 50,000 hadronic Z0 decay events collected by the SLD experiment. The data were corrected [12] for detector bias effects such as acceptance, resolution, and inefficiency, as well as for the effects of initial-state radiation and hadronisation, to arrive at `parton-level' distributions.

9

For each observable we employed the EVENT program [42] to calculate the coefficients A and B in Eq. (1). We then fitted the O(ff2s) calculation to the measured parton-level distributions, using first the physical scale _ = MZ , by minimising O/2 w.r.t. variation of \Lambda MS. In each case the fit range was chosen so as to exclude the 2-jet region, where resummation [21] of higher-order perturbative contributions is required [12], as well as the 4-jet region, where the O(ff2s) calculation is not expected to reproduce the data accurately; these ranges are indicated in Fig. 1. Each resulting \Lambda MS value was translated into ffs(M 2Z ); these are shown, with experimental errors [12], in Fig. 2(a). It can be seen that there is considerable scatter among the 15 ffs(M 2Z ) values. Since the same data sample was used to measure each observable, and since the observables are highly correlated, this scatter is very significant. Similar results have been observed previously [16]. The scatter can be interpreted as arising from uncalculated higher-order perturbative QCD contributions, which a priori may be of different sign and magnitude for the different observables. Taking an unweighted average over all 15 ffs(M 2Z ) values, and a corresponding r.m.s. deviation, yields 1:

ffs(M 2Z ) = 0:1265 \Sigma 0:0076 (physical scale): We repeated this procedure using the experimentally-optimised-scale approach. In this case a simultaneous fit of \Lambda MS and _ to each distribution was performed; the fitted value of _ is indicated in Fig. 1. The resulting pairs of \Lambda MS and _ values were translated to ffs(M 2Z ), which are also shown in Fig. 2(a)2. Again, there is large scatter among the 15 ffs(M 2Z ) values. It should be noted that for most observables

