closely related to the momentum-transfer involved in the physical process, namely the radiation of soft and/or collinear gluons; the behaviour of the PMS and FAC scales in the two-jet limit does not appear to satisfy this expectation.

For each observable we then fitted the O(ff2s) calculation to the measured distribution, using in turn the PMS, FAC and BLM scales, to determine \Lambda MS and hence ffs(M 2Z ). The results are shown in Fig. 2(b); in the case of oblateness an acceptable fit with the BLM scale could not be obtained. For each observable it can be seen that the PMS- and FAC-derived ffs(M 2Z ) values are very similar, whereas, typically, the BLM-derived ffs(M 2Z ) value differs from them. This behaviour follows from the correlation between the scale value (Fig. 1) and the corresponding \Lambda MS required to fit the data [22]. Comparing Figs. 2(a) and 2(b) it can be seen that for a given observable the PMS- and FAC-derived ffs(M 2Z ) values are often, though not always, close to that determined using the experimentally-optimised scale. Furthermore, for most observables the PMS-, FAC- and BLM-derived ffs(M 2Z ) values all lie within the range encompassed by the _-variation considered in [12], though for ae, BW , DP2 , DP 02 , DG2 and (BT ), the BLM- (PMS/FAC-) derived values lie below this range.

The most striking feature of Fig. 2(b) is that, for any of the PMS, FAC or BLM scale choices, there is considerable scatter among the ffs(M 2Z ) values from all the observables. In each case, taking an unweighted average over all the ffs(M 2Z ) values and a corresponding r.m.s. deviation yields 1:

